SIMPLE: promoter
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Promoter
<hw>Pro*mot"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One
who, or that which, forwards, advances, or promotes; an encourager;
<as>as, a <ex>promoter</ex> of charity or philosophy</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically, one who sets on foot, and takes the
preliminary steps in, a scheme for the organization of a corporation, a
joint-stock company, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One who excites; <as>as, a <ex>promoter</ex> of
sedition</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An informer; a makebate.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Tusser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Genetics)</fld> <def>The region of a DNA molecule
to which RNA polymerase binds to initiate the process of transcription,
i.e. the synthesis of RNA whose sequence is determined by the sequence
of the DNA adjacent to the promoter site; also, the sequence of bases in
the DNA at such a promoter site.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A substance that increases the
activity of a catalyst, when present in small quantity in the reaction
mixture.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>promotion</ent>⟦br⟧
